01/12/2002
BELGRADE, Yugoslavia -- Yugoslav President Vojislav Kostunica said Saturday (30 November) that the next round of the presidential elections in Serbia should be the last one. If the 8 December vote fails to elect new president, Serbia should hold early parliamentary elections, according to Kostunica, who received the most votes in the first election and the run off.
In other election news, Filip Vujanovic, vice president of the Democratic Party of Socialists, has officially registered as a candidate in Montenegro's 22 December presidential race. He is currently serving as acting president, taking over the duties of Milo Djukanovic, who stepped aside to become prime minister. (Vecernje novosti - 01/12/02; Tanjug - 30/11/02)
